    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the dice thing makes sense for the concept, but you mentioned it's \"spooky\"—i've heard Einstein call it \"spooky action at a distance.\" can you explain why it's considered spooky or \"unexplained\" compared to how things usually work in physics?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the \"spooky action at a distance\" is indeed a term that Albert Einstein used to describe his discomfort with quantum entanglement. He found it spooky because it defied the classical idea that objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings. In the world of classical physics, it's like saying that if you shake one dice, the other one on the moon doesn't feel it at all. But with entanglement, it's as if the dice are connected by an invisible, magical string that instantly teleports the shake from one to the other, no matter the distance. This goes against our everyday experience and intuition, making it seem like magic or something out of a fairy tale. Einstein couldn't wrap his head around how something could be connected in such a mysterious way without any visible means of communication. It's like having a secret language between the dice that no one else can understand, and it just doesn't fit with the way we normally think about the world.",
      "source": "target",
